{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/menopause/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"5b768dab-f7db-50c3-8686-0d363f36e74d","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 7c5e2a6f-7c71-4b17-b375-4a0de1a67c6e --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 7c5e2a6f-7c71-4b17-b375-4a0de1a67c6e -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 796ad871-10ec-4d40-97c5-f72b94e5b725 --><!-- begin field b78845df-ffee-4422-973c-a4c26131a8a7 --><p><strong>Menopausal symptoms are extremely common but are likely to be under-recognized and under-treated [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">NICE, 2019</a>]. A woman's ethnicity, cultural, religious, sociological, and nutritional factors may modify the intensity and incidence of menopausal symptoms [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Hickey, 2017</a>].</strong></p><ul><li>Vasomotor symptoms<ul><li>Vasomotor symptoms (hot flushes and night sweats) are the most commonly reported symptoms, occurring in about 80% of postmenopausal women, with 25% of these reporting a severe impact on quality of life [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Hickey, 2017</a>].</li><li>Similarly, a US review of community-based longitudinal studies found that the prevalence of hot flushes in postmenopausal women reached up to 79% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Woods, 2005</a>].</li><li>A multicentre, multiethnic longitudinal cohort study of US women reported that [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Green, 2009</a>]:<ul><li>Vasomotor symptoms were more prevalent among African-American and Hispanic women.</li><li>Vasomotor symptoms were less prevalent among Japanese and Chinese women, and the lowest reported prevalence was among non-Hispanic Caucasian women.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Genitourinary syndrome of menopause<ul><li>An Italian multicentre cross-sectional study of 747 women aged 40â€“55 years found genitourinary syndrome of menopause was diagnosed in 36.8% of women, and most signs and symptoms had an age-related increase in frequency and intensity [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Cagnacci, 2019</a>].</li><li>Similarly, expert opinion in a review article notes that genitourinary symptoms affect up to 50% of women during menopause [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Hill, 2016</a>].</li></ul></li><li>Premature ovarian insufficiency (POI)<ul><li>A pooled analysis of nine observational studies of the general female population in high-income countries (n = 51,450 postmenopausal women) found the prevalence of [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Mishra, 2017</a>]:<ul><li>Premature menopause was 2%.</li><li>Early menopause was 7.6%.</li></ul></li><li>A meta-analysis of 31 global cohort and cross-sectional studies found the pooled prevalence of [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/references/\">Golezar, 2019</a>]:<ul><li>Premature ovarian insufficiency was 3.7%.</li><li>Early menopause was 12.2%.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field b78845df-ffee-4422-973c-a4c26131a8a7 --><!-- end item 796ad871-10ec-4d40-97c5-f72b94e5b725 -->","topic":{"id":"69003588-b736-585d-8a5d-7ca0e916caa5","topicId":"f75fa6a7-10c6-4887-9cf1-3ea14d7f353c","topicName":"Menopause","slug":"menopause","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2020","chapters":[{"id":"0359e5fa-1342-5767-a4da-2f8b5cd2b6db","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"c978ff88-dda8-5879-a0